Closure is an inner function, that is accessible outside of its parent function's scope while maintaining its connection to the parent's variables and other data. This can be don to keep some data private and purposely expose other data.
To accomplish this, an anonymous function can be immediately invoked. In this function, data we wish to keep  private can be processed. Usually this data would be removed from memory via JavaScript's "garbage collection" memory clearing process. If this function returns a function, let's call it a child function, that accesses data from the parent function, the parent's data will remain in memory. In this situation, the only access to the parent function's data will be via whatever had been set up in the child function. In addition, every time the child function is invoked, a new function scope is created for the child function. The parent function scope is only created once. This means that we can invoke the child function to change a variable in the parent and the next time we invoke the child function the variable in the parent will still reflect the change. 

This can be considered state management and might not be as useful today given other options to manage state. Still, this process can be used to protect sensitive data or even just a to keep a counter variable from being accidentally increased.

Some examples
// For comparison, this is a counter without closure
let counter = 0;

function add1 () {
	counter++;
	return counter;
}

console.log(add1());  // 1
console.log(add1());  // 2
// The counter becomes unpredictable when it can be altered elswhere
counter++;
console.log(add1());  // 4


// This is a counter with closure
const add1 = (function () {
  let counter = 0;

  return function () {
	counter++;
	return counter;
  };
})();
console.log(add1());  // 1
console.log(add1());  // 2
console.log(add1());  // 3
counter++;// error: counter is not defined
console.log(add1());

// Another, more complex example
// In this travelAgent() in the child function made available, while 
// the "trip" variable and agent() function are accessible through 
// travelAgent(). The book() function, is only accessible through agent().
function vacation() {
	var trip;

	function travelAgent(itinerary) {
		agent(itinerary);
		return trip;
	}

	function agent(itinerary) {
		if (itinerary === 'Orlando') {
			trip = ['Orlando', 'Disney', 'Universal'];
			book();
		}
	}

	function book() {
		trip.push('booked');
	}
	return travelAgent;
}

var myVacation = vacation();

console.log(myVacation('Orlando'));

// Array [ "Orlando", "Disney", "Universal", "booked" ]

