In CSS, there is a general higher priority given to the rules added last as opposed to first. This is higher priority is not the final work, however, as there are guidelines within the CSS specification to allow for rules to override others based on specificity.

Style Sheets are generally better than inline-styles because they allow for separation of the styling and provide the developer a central location for making changes. In addition, we can also affect as few or as many elements as we want, where inline-styles only affect themselves (though inheritance can cascade 

Specificity is the system the browser uses to decide which CSS declarations will be applied. Specificity is based on how specific to an element the rule is. In this, an inline-style is directly on the element and thus the most specific, though not usually a good idea because it eliminates the usefulness of a style sheet. 

	An ID is meant to address one specific element, and so this is next in line. 

	A class covers any number of elements, making it very non-specific and, because of this, third in line. 

	Type selectors, like "div" or " h1" are even less specific to an element, and are fourth in line.

	With the above in mind, there is a way to make make a CSS rule more specific. This can be done by chaining together additional references to the element. This can be adding more related detail from the element, like additional classes on the element, or even detail from the elements parents, like a parents ID or a class: 

	#parent-id .child-class { ...declarations }

	The above would no overrule this:

	#child-id

It is possible to override all of the specificity rules using "!important". While this will seem to make dealing with CSS specificity easier, it is usually a bad practice as it breaks CSS specificity order. In addition, trying to use "!important" multiple times on the same element enters into the same specificity rules one might be attempting to avoid. 

Drop this example into an online editor, like https://codepen.io/pen/, to see specificity and inheritance in action:

CSS
	body {
		color: skyblue;
	}

	 h4 {
		color: darksalmon !important;
	}
	h4 {
		color: black;
	}
	#outer-wrap-one {
		color: seagreen;
	}

	h2 {
		color: red;
	}

	.orange-text {
		color: orange;
	}

	#purple-text {
		color: purple;
	}


   

HTML
