This addresses what happens when passing data from one variable to another. More specifically, this is about where variables point. 

The original variable points to a place in memory. The new variable can either point to the same place in memory, which means the reference to the data was passed, or the new variable can point to a new place in memory that contains the same data, which means the values were passed to the new memory location.

The main reason this is important is shown by the results of changing either variable. If only a reference was passed, meaning both variables point to the same data at the same memory location, then changing a value will change change it for both variables, as well as any others pointing to the same place in memory.

If the actual values were passed and reside at a new location in memory, changing the values at the new memory location will only be visible with the new variable (and any others pointing to that location). The original variable is still pointing at the old memory location and remains unchanged.

Examples:
let example1 = 1;
let example2 = example1;
example2++;

console.log(example1, ' - ', example2);

const example3 = {
  weapon: 'lightsaber'
};
const example4 = {
  ...example3
};
example4.name = 'Darth Vader';
console.log(example3, ' - ', example4);

