Responsive design is an approach to wed design where we create content that adjusts smoothly to various screen sizes. We can use relative units, like percentages and/or use media queries to make sure that the content and overall flow keeps the look, feel and function of the interface no matter what device or device orientation is being used.

We have a number of options these days. The following are options that can be used independently or in any combination we wish:

	CSS grid system: This is a grid system that can adjust to the screen size and makes for easy and predictable placement of elements.


	Relative units: Sizing content with percentages ensures there will not be any items that break the flow on small screens. 

	Flexbox: Flex box properties allow us to use an intuitive approach to keep content positioned in a predictable way regardless of screen size.

	Media queries: While media queries are powerful and very useful, these are generally meant to be a last resort. Not because there is anything wrong with them, only because, ideally, we can have content sized and positioned predictably and smoothly using the tools described above. This makes for more consistency across current commonly used screen sizes along with future devices with different screen sizes and a variety of less common, but still used, screen sizes. 

		There are times where we do need to set a point where content needs to have specific rules applied. These points we set up, called breakpoints, will usually correspond to specific screen sizes or device orientations. We can have breakpoints at desktop, tablet and smartphone sizes, plus additional media queries for portrait or landscape orientations.


