This might sound like a silly question, but questions like this sometimes are used to get us to show our understanding of basic, but often needed, aspects of CSS. This will usually be a screening question, so a descriptive verbal outline will needed, not actual code.

To begin, we need to target our element via ID, or by class for multiple elements. We then want to set an equal width and height, perhaps 100px each. From there, we can either set the border for a few pixels or a background color or even both. This way we can see it. At that point, we have a square.

Making that square a circle simply requires a border-radius of 50% all of the way around. 

Now, that is a fixed width square or circle. We could make it responsive by using a percentage as the width and an equal percentage as padding-bottom. If there is content in the square or circle, one way to keep the sides equal would be to absolutely position the content. Ultimately, this is just an option. There are many ways to approach graphics in CSS, and purpose and the rest of the document will play into a plan for making the graphics responsive.


Paste this example into an online editor, like https://codepen.io/pen/, to see the square and circle:

