This is generally asked to get an idea of how much someone pays attention to good practices and, ultimately, will write easier to understand code and have an easier time jumping into someone else's code.

General naming conventions:
-	Names should be brief, but descriptive enough that the average non-developer could understand. For example, using "d = new Date()" might serve brevity, but can make no sense later in the program and require extra effort to understand. Conversely, "theDateForTheDayTheAppIsRun = new Date()" is clear, but unnecessarily long. Simply "todaysDate = new Date()" is brief and easily understood.

A few JavaScript examples can be:
- Camel case for variables: const lastName = 'Kenobi'
- Pascal case for classes: class MainCharacter { }
- "is" or "has" prefix for booleans.
- Function calls that will be returning something can start with have a descriptive verb ("update", "get", etc).
- As few variables as possible. This is not really a naming convention, but it greatly affects the abilty for the names of the variables that do get used to be easier to follow and keep track of.
- Do not re-use variable names.
- In many cases it is better not to make a variable equal itself with modification. This can be difficult to follow through and can often be better served with a new, variable descriptively named to match the newly formed data.
- When reasonable, if a specific item in an array is being used, assign a more descriptive variable: const updatedFileId = changes[0]
- Property names that do not need to be prefixed with the class name. 
	We do not need: class Car {
								constructor(brand, purchaseDate) {
								this.carName = brand;
								this.carYear = purchaseDate;
							}
} 
	Instead, we can use: class Car {
								constructor(brand) {
								this.name = brand;
								this.year = purchaseDate;
							} 
							// in use it will still be descriptive
							const myCar = new Car();
							myCar,name = 'Jeep';
							myCar.year = '2017';
- Avoid "magic" numbers, or numbers without a name, when possible. 
	We want to avoid: const forwardMovement = duration * 3;
	We can use: const rate = 3;
				  forwardMovement = duration * rate;


CSS & HTML examples:
- Use nicely cascading rules to make for as few selectors as possible.
- Kabab case for selectors: .inner-wrap
- Descriptive selector names. This can be the BEM (Block, Element, Modifier) method or similar.
- Try to avoid using the same name for an ID and a class. These are technically independent from each other, but this can cause confusion for a developer.

