Comparing to see if two objects are not really just one referencing the other: Object.is(). This will tell us if one is really just a variable that was passed a reference to the original object, like with: const var1 = obj1; This is only a reference, so Object.is(var1, obj1) will equal true. If so, the values will always be identical.

Comparing unique objects can be a little more involved. There is a loose approach and a more strict approach. 

We can test the number of entries in each, as a different number of entries would indicate they are different. We can do this by checking if one has more keys than the other using Object.keys().length or Object.getOwnPropertyNames().length.
When iterating through the objects, we must also account for the possibility of nested arrays and/or objects. These might even go many levels deep.

One way is to turn both objects into strings using JSON.stringify() and then compare the strings. This will ONLY work if we know the keys will always be IN THE SAME ORDER. When using this method, any variance, like a key being in a different place, will cause the comparison to fail even though the values might be identical.

A more strict approach is to iterate through each object and check the key-value pair against the other. This will work even if the keys are not in the same order. 


const user1 = {
  first: 'Lando',
  last: 'Calrissian'
};
const user2 = {
  first: 'Lando',
  last: 'Calrissian'
};


// Direct comparison
console.log(user1 === user2);  // false

// Stringify process
const stringObj1 = JSON.stringify(user1);
const stringObj2 = JSON.stringify(user2);

console.log(typeof stringObj1);  // string
console.log(stringObj1 === stringObj2);  // true



// Iterating process possibiltiy
function isSameObject (obj1, obj2) {
  const props1 = Object.getOwnPropertyNames(obj1);
  const props2 = Object.getOwnPropertyNames(obj2);

  if (props1.length !== props2.length) {
    return false;
  }

  for (let i = 0; i < props1.length; i++) {
    const property = props1[i];

    if (props1[property] !== props2[property]) {
      return false;
    }
  }

  return true;
}

console.log(isSameObject(user1, user2));  // true

