Flexbox is one-dimensional, meaning we can control the arranging children across a horizontal plane or a vertical plane, but never both. Flexbox will move elements in both directions when set for wrapping, like a vertical line wrapping the elements to the next line, but we do not control this. We choose either vertical and horizontal, unlike a grid system. 

	Flexbox requires only: 'display: flex' to set up, which makes it very quick and easy. 

	While Flexbox could be used on a whole page or large section and function well, it is ideal for handling smaller areas or situations where actual end placement is not important, just fluid response to different screen sizes.

		Basic setup:
		.container {
		  display: flex;
		}

CSS Grid is two-dimension, meaning we can control the layout both horizontally and vertically. This makes it ideal for page layouts and large areas, though it would stil function well for one direction and small areas. CSS Grid is responsive and gives the user a lot of control. The only downside might be that the setup can be a little, sometimes a lot, more involved than Flexbox. 

	Basic setup:
	.container {
	  display: grid;
	  grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(15rem, 1fr));
	  grid-gap: 1rem;
	}

