A pseudo-element in CSS is similar to a pseudo-class in that it uses a keyword added to a selector, but he similarities end there. CSS pseudo-elements let us style a specific part of elements or even add to the beginning or end of the element. In addition, a pseudo-element will use double colons between the keyword and the selector. Technically, because this double-colon convention was not in place early on, the spec still allows this. That said, it is still expected that double colons are used.


A few examples:

::after - This creates an inline pseudo-element as the lst child of an element.

::before - Similar to the above, this creates an inline pseudo-element as the first child of an element.

::first-letter - This will apply styles to the first letter of the first line of an element.

::first-line - This works like ::first-letter, but the style will apply to the whole line. What qualifies for the first line will depend on the width of the element, font size and other similar factors.

::selection - When the user highlights a section, usually by clicking and dragging the mouse across text, we can style this highlighted area using the ::selection pseudo-element.


Drop this example into an online editor, like https://codepen.io/pen/, to see a few of the pseudo-elements work their magic:

