A pseudo-class is a keyword added to a selector, marked with a colon : in between. This designates the rule to apply to a special state of the element. These special states are numerous, but a few are:

:checked - This shows a checked or toggled-on state for any radio (<input type="radio">), checkbox (<input type="checkbox">), or option (<option> in a <select>) element.
:active - This shows an element is being activated by the user. This will often be a button or similar action element, but, technically, can be any element. Activated would usually mean the user clicked on the element.

:hover - When a user interacts with an element without actually activating it, the element will have the hover state. This is most often achieved by hovering the cursor over the element using a mouse, but can also be achieved on touchscreens. The later can be a problem, as the actual application of the hover state varies on different browsers and devices. Due to this, the hover state should not be necessary for relaying information. For example, a link or button should not require the user hover over it in order to see it is clickable.

:visited - This is an link that has already been activated.

:first-child - As it sounds, this is the first element to a parent.

:last-child - Opposite of first-child, this is the last element to a parent.

:nth-last-child(Xn) - This element is the one that is the given number away (X) from the end.

:nth-of-type - This takes the type(tag name) and given number and then assigns this pseudo-class to elements that fit this pattern.


